  "prompt": "The girl I like, tells me to behave casual with her, because someone is teasing her with me! What should I do?",
  "response": "Okay, this is a classic situation. Here's a breakdown of what's likely happening and what you can do, balancing respect for her wishes with your own feelings:\n\n**Understanding the Situation**\n\n*   **She's likely uncomfortable with the attention:** The teasing is making her feel self-conscious. It's possible she doesn't want to confirm or deny anything until she's figured out how she feels, or how to handle the situation.\n*   **She might like you, but isn't ready for it to be public:** She could have feelings for you, but is worried about what others will think, or perhaps she isn't ready for a relationship. She might be dealing with peer pressure.\n*   **She might not reciprocate your feelings:** It's possible she doesn't feel the same way, and is trying to let you down gently by saying this.\n*   **She wants to protect your friendship:** Even if she doesn't have romantic feelings, she may value your friendship and doesn't want this situation to ruin it.\n\n**What You Should Do**\n\n1.  **Respect Her Request:** This is the most important thing. If she's asked you to behave casually, then do it. Don't push the issue. This shows her that you respect her boundaries and care about her feelings.\n2.  **Observe Her Body Language and Actions:** While you're behaving casually, pay attention to how she acts around you when others *aren't* around. Does she seem more relaxed, more open, or more engaged? This can give you a better sense of her true feelings.\n3.  **Focus on Being a Good Friend:** Continue to be supportive, kind, and fun to be around. Show her that you value her as a person, regardless of the romantic potential. This will strengthen your bond, whatever form it takes.\n4.  **Don't Overanalyze Every Interaction:** It's easy to get caught up in trying to decipher hidden meanings, but try to avoid this. It will only drive you crazy. Just focus on enjoying her company and being a good friend.\n5.  **Give Her Time:** Let her work through her feelings and the situation with the teasing. Pushing her will likely backfire.\n6.  **Consider Talking to Her (Later):** After some time has passed and the teasing has hopefully died down, you *might* consider a gentle conversation. Use \"I\" statements:\n    *   \"Hey, I just wanted to check in. I understand you wanted me to act casual because of the teasing, and I've been trying to respect that. I just wanted to know if there's anything else I should be aware of.\"\n    *   \"I value our friendship, and I also wanted to be honest that I do have feelings for you. I'm happy to keep things casual if that's what you prefer, but I just wanted to be open about it.\"\n    *   **Be prepared for any answer.** She might tell you she needs more time, that she doesn't reciprocate your feelings, or that she's starting to feel something too.\n\n**What NOT to Do**\n\n*   **Don't pressure her:** This will make her uncomfortable and could damage your relationship.\n*   **Don't talk to the people who are teasing her:** That will likely make the situation worse and could embarrass her further.\n*   **Don't ignore her or act cold:** This might make her think you're angry or disinterested.\n*   **Don't become overly jealous or possessive:** This will be a major red flag.\n*   **Don't confide in too many people about your feelings:** This could get back to her and put her in an awkward position.\n\n**In summary:** The best approach is to respect her wishes, be a good friend, and give her time to sort things out. It's a delicate situation, so proceed with sensitivity and understanding. Good luck!\n",
